From: ROCm runtime/driver team <gpu-driver@amd.com>
Subject: [PATCH RFC v2.3] amdkfd: K-5 V2.3 lookup-at-uncharge to fix kfd_process kref leak

Replace the kgd_mem.kfdp_owner kref-storage design from V2/V2.1/V2.2
with a "lookup-at-uncharge" pattern: at charge time we still call
kfd_lookup_process_by_mm() to get a kfd_process for the precheck, but
we drop the ref immediately after marking the BO. At uncharge time
(unpin / free / error rollback), we look up kfd_process again via
current->mm. If the lookup fails (cross-mm uncharge: peer-memory
reaper after process exit, dma-buf importer free, mmu_notifier
release running in workqueue context with no current->mm) we leave
the per-process counter stale rather than leak a kref.

Motivation
----------
V2.1 and V2.2 both leaked kfd_process krefs when the customer
workload exercised RDMA peer-memory reaper backlog. After ~14 minutes
of soak, /sys/module/amdgpu/refcnt accumulated to ~65,500 (close to
U16_MAX). Root cause: each charge took a kfd_process kref and stored
it in kgd_mem.kfdp_owner; at uncharge the matching put runs only if
the unpin path is reached normally. Reaper-driven unpin runs in a
workqueue with no current task, can race with kfd_process_destroy(),
and the orphaned BO holds the kref indefinitely. V2.2 added an
explicit cleanup at err_reserve_limit but did not cover the reaper
case, so the leak persisted.

Tradeoff
--------
Cross-mm uncharge cannot find the original kfd_process and leaves
its per-process pin counter stale. This is bounded and benign:

  - The K-5 cap is recomputed from cgroup memcg on every charge, so
    a stale counter only shrinks effective headroom for the SAME
    process whose mm is dying. New processes get a fresh cap.
  - kfd_process is destroyed via kfd_process_destroy()
    (kfd_chardev release path), which also runs from the dying mm
    and zeroes the counter when the kfd_process struct is freed.
  - No global counter, no cgroup counter, no kernel module refcnt
    sees this drift.

Patch summary
-------------
Removed:
  - kgd_mem.kfdp_owner field (was: void *, struct kfd_process *)

Kept:
  - kgd_mem.kfdp_charged_bytes (mirror of charged amount)
  - kgd_mem.kfdp_host_charged (which counter to roll back to)

Modified call sites in amdgpu_amdkfd_gpuvm.c (8 sites):
  1. amdgpu_amdkfd_gpuvm_pin_bo:
     a. RDMA charge (drop kref after charge)
     b. RDMA charge rollback when rdma_quota_try_charge fails
     c. pin_non_vram_rollback (out: target)
     d. err_accounting (err_accounting: target)
  2. amdgpu_amdkfd_gpuvm_unpin_bo:
     e. RDMA unpin (was the worst leaker -- reaper path)
  3. amdgpu_amdkfd_gpuvm_alloc_memory_of_gpu:
     f. host-pin charge (drop kref after charge)
     g. reserve_mem_limit failure rollback
     h. err_reserve_limit catch-all
  4. amdgpu_amdkfd_gpuvm_free_memory_of_gpu:
     i. top-of-function host-pin uncharge

Tested on hjbog-srdc-22, MI308X, host 5.10.134, amdgpu 6.14.14:
  - V2.2 baseline: refcnt grows to 65,527 in 14 minutes of mr_burn +
    hip_host_burn churn.
  - V2.3 (this patch): refcnt stable at 0..3 across same workload.
  - K-5 cap enforcement: identical to V2.2 (regression matrix passes).

Signed-off-by: ROCm runtime/driver team <gpu-driver@amd.com>
---
 drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_amdkfd.h        |  20 ++--
 drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_amdkfd_gpuvm.c  | 110 +++++++++++++--------
 2 files changed, 80 insertions(+), 50 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_amdkfd.h b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_amdkfd.h
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_amdkfd.h
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_amdkfd.h
@@ -105,15 +105,21 @@ struct kgd_mem {
 	bool rdma_quota_charged;
 
 	/*
-	 * K-5 V2: per-process pin owner.
-	 * Saved at first charge so the unpin path can decrement the right
-	 * kfd_process even when called from a different mm (e.g. unpin
-	 * triggered by process B for a BO charged by process A).
-	 * Owner ref is taken via kfd_lookup_process_by_mm() at charge time;
-	 * dropped via kfd_unref_process() at uncharge or destroy.
+	 * K-5 V2.3: per-process pin accounting (no owner ref).
+	 * kfdp_charged_bytes records how much we charged (so unpin/free
+	 * can roll back the same amount). kfdp_host_charged tells the
+	 * uncharge code whether the bytes are on the host_pin counter
+	 * (true: GTT/USERPTR/host) or rdma_pin counter (false: VRAM).
+	 *
+	 * Uncharge re-looks up kfd_process via current->mm at unpin/free
+	 * time. Cross-mm paths (peer-memory reaper after process exit,
+	 * dma-buf importer free, mmu_notifier release in workqueue) will
+	 * fail the lookup and leave the per-process counter stale; this
+	 * is acceptable because the K-5 cap is recomputed from cgroup
+	 * memcg on every charge, so a stale entry only shrinks effective
+	 * headroom for the (already dying) process. Storing a kref here
+	 * was the V2/V2.1 design but caused module refcnt leaks under
+	 * peer-memory reaper backlog -- removed in V2.3.
 	 */
-	void *kfdp_owner;            /* struct kfd_process * */
 	u64   kfdp_charged_bytes;    /* mirror of how much we charged */
 	bool  kfdp_host_charged;     /* true if charged against host_pin counter */
 };

